\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
-R_{1} & = & z_{1}\left(1+\frac{z_{R}^{2}}{z_{1}^{2}}\right)\\
R_{2} & = & z_{2}\left(1+\frac{z_{R}^{2}}{z_{2}^{2}}\right)\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

con la ligadura adicional de que 
\begin_inset Formula $l=z_{2}-z_{1}$
\end_inset 

.
 Estas tres ecuaciones deberán resolverse para obtener 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{2}$
\end_inset 

 y 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{R}$
\end_inset 

.
 Más significativos que 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}$
\end_inset 

 y 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}$
\end_inset 

 son los llamados 
\emph on 
parámetros del resonador
\emph default 

\begin_inset LatexCommand \index{parámetros del resonador}

\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g_{1}=1-\frac{l}{R_{1}}\qquad g_{2}=1-\frac{l}{R_{2}}\label{eq:def-g1-g2}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 En términos de estos parámetros se reescribe el sistema de ecuaciones
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
g_{1} & = & 1+\frac{l}{z_{1}\left(1+z_{R}^{2}/z_{1}^{2}\right)}\label{eq:g1-de-z1-zR}\\
g_{2} & = & 1-\frac{l}{z_{2}\left(1+z_{R}^{2}/z_{2}^{2}\right)}\label{eq:g2-de-z2-zR}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 Para resolverlo se puede eliminar primero 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{R}^{2}$
\end_inset 

 entre ambas y usar 
\begin_inset Formula $l=z_{2}-z_{1}$
\end_inset 

 para despejar 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}$
\end_inset 

 o 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{2}$
\end_inset 

.
 Se obtiene así
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
z_{1}=-\frac{g_{2}(1-g_{1})}{g_{1}+g_{2}-2g_{1}g_{2}}l;\quad z_{2}=\frac{g_{1}(1-g_{2})}{g_{1}+g_{2}-2g_{1}g_{2}}l;\quad z_{R}^{2}=\frac{g_{1}g_{2}(1-g_{1}g_{2})}{(g_{1}+g_{2}-2g_{1}g_{2})^{2}}l^{2}\label{eq:z1-z2-zR}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 De 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{R}\left(w_{0}\right)$
\end_inset 

 (ec.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:relacion-w0-zR}

\end_inset 

) obtenemos entonces la cintura del haz,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w_{0}^{2}=\frac{l\lambda}{\pi}\sqrt{\frac{g_{1}g_{2}(1-g_{1}g_{2})}{(g_{1}+g_{2}-2g_{1}g_{2})^{2}}}\label{eq:w0-fn-de-g1-g2}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Y usando 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(z\right)$
\end_inset 

 (ec.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:w-de-z}

\end_inset 

) tendremos los radios del haz en los espejos, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}=w\left(z_{1}\right)$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{2}=w\left(z_{2}\right)$
\end_inset 

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
w_{1}^{2} & = & \frac{l\lambda}{\pi}\sqrt{\frac{g_{2}}{g_{1}(1-g_{1}g_{2})}}\label{eq:w-de-z1}\\
w_{2}^{2} & = & \frac{l\lambda}{\pi}\sqrt{\frac{g_{1}}{g_{2}(1-g_{1}g_{2})}}\label{eq:w-de-z2}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

Si existe el haz gaussiano capaz de formar la onda estacionaria, la cintura
 de haz deberá ser real, es decir que en 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:w0-fn-de-g1-g2}

\end_inset 


